1️⃣ Distributed Transactions Problem (30 min)
What is a Distributed Transaction?

A single logical transaction that spans multiple services / databases.

Example in Banking:

Transfer ₹1000 from Account A → Account B


But in microservices:

Debit happens in Account Service DB

Credit happens in Payment/Transfer Service DB

Two different databases ❗
One DB transaction cannot cover both.

The Core Problem

What if system crashes in middle?

Scenario

Debit ₹1000 from A ✅

System crashes before credit ❌

Now:

Money removed from A

Not added to B

💥 Data inconsistency (Banking disaster)

This is called Partial Commit Problem.

Why Single DB Transactions Don’t Work

Local DB transaction guarantees ACID only inside ONE database.

But in microservices:

Multiple DBs

Multiple services

Network calls

Async processing

So no global transaction manager.

Classical Solution — 2 Phase Commit (2PC)
Phase 1 — Prepare

All services ask DB:

“Can you commit?”

Lock resources

If all say YES → go next

Phase 2 — Commit

Coordinator says:

“Commit now”

Problems with 2PC

Very slow

DB locks for long time

Not scalable

If coordinator crashes → system stuck

Rarely used in modern systems

👉 Banks avoid 2PC in microservices.

Modern Solution — Saga Pattern (Industry Standard)

Instead of one big transaction, break into multiple small transactions.

Each step commits independently.

If something fails → Compensation (Undo).

Saga Example — Money Transfer
Step-by-step

Debit Account A → commit

Credit Account B → commit

If Step 2 fails:

Compensation → Refund A

So system becomes eventually consistent.

Two Types of Saga
1. Choreography (Event-based)

No central controller.

Transfer Service → Event → Account Service (Debit)
                  → Event → Payment Service (Credit)
                  → Event → Notification


Services react to events.

Pros:

Loose coupling

Scalable

Cons:

Hard to track flow

2. Orchestration (Central Coordinator)

One service controls flow.

Orchestrator:
  → Debit Service
  → Credit Service
  → If fail → Refund Service


Pros:

Easier control

Easier debugging

Cons:

Slight coupling

Banking Reality

Banks usually use:

Saga pattern

Compensation logic

Idempotency

Transaction logs

Retry + Dead-letter queues

Audit trail

Because money must never be lost.

