2️⃣ Exactly-Once vs At-Least-Once Delivery

This topic is about message / transaction delivery guarantees in distributed systems (Kafka, queues, retries, banking transfers).

Why this matters in Banking

During money transfer systems use:

Retry on failure

Network calls

Async processing (Kafka / Events)

Without proper guarantee:

❌ Money may be lost

❌ Money may be duplicated

❌ Double debit / double credit

So delivery semantics are critical.

3 Types of Delivery Guarantees
1️⃣ At-Most-Once (Fire & Forget)

Message sent once — no retry

If failure happens → message LOST ❌

Example:

Debit event sent → network failed → credit never happens


Result → Money disappears 💥

👉 Not acceptable in banking

2️⃣ At-Least-Once (Retry enabled)

Message will be delivered 1 or more times

If failure → system retries.

Problem → Duplicates possible

Example:

Transfer request sent
Retry triggered
Same transfer executed twice → double debit 💥


👉 This is what MOST systems use
👉 Must combine with Idempotency

3️⃣ Exactly-Once (Perfect but complex)

Message delivered ONLY once — no loss, no duplicate

Sounds perfect but:

Hard to implement

Slow

Requires distributed coordination

Kafka transactions needed

Not fully “exact” in real world

👉 Used carefully in fintech, not everywhere.

Banking Reality

Most banking systems use:

At-Least-Once + Idempotency = Practically Exactly-Once


Because:

Retry ensures no money loss

Idempotency prevents duplicate transfer

What is Idempotency?

Same request executed multiple times → result stays same

Example:

Transfer ₹1000 with transactionId = TXN123


If request comes again:

System checks:

TXN123 already processed → IGNORE duplicate


So no double debit 👍

Visual Example

Without idempotency:

Retry happens twice

Debit ₹1000 → OK
Debit ₹1000 → AGAIN ❌
Balance wrong


With idempotency:

Debit ₹1000 → OK
Retry → TXN exists → ignore
Balance correct ✅

Where duplicates come from

Network timeout

Client retry

Server retry

Kafka re-delivery

Load balancer retry

User double click

How to implement Idempotency (Banking Standard)

Generate unique transactionId

Store in DB

Before processing → check if exists

If exists → ignore duplicate

