4️⃣ Event-Driven Architecture (EDA) — Async Banking Flow
What is Event-Driven Architecture?

Instead of direct service-to-service calls, systems communicate using events/messages.

A service produces an event → other services consume and react.

Why Banking Uses EDA

Bank transfer involves many side actions:

Debit / Credit

Notification (SMS / Email)

Audit logging

Fraud detection

Analytics

Ledger update

Doing all synchronously = slow ❌
So we use async event flow.

Traditional (Synchronous)
Transfer Service
   → Notification Service
   → Audit Service
   → Fraud Service
   → Analytics


Problems:

Slow response

Tight coupling

One failure breaks whole flow

Event-Driven (Async)
Transfer Service → Kafka/Event → Notification Service
                              → Audit Service
                              → Fraud Detection
                              → Analytics


Transfer finishes fast ✅
Other services run independently ✅

Core Components
1. Producer

Service that publishes event

Example:

TransferCompletedEvent

2. Broker (Kafka / RabbitMQ)

Stores and distributes events.

3. Consumer

Services that listen and react.

Example:

Notification Service → send SMS

Audit Service → store logs

Fraud Service → risk analysis

Banking Transfer Event Flow
User initiates transfer
   ↓
Transfer Service (DB transaction)
   ↓
Publish Event → TRANSFER_SUCCESS
   ↓
Kafka
   ↓
Consumers:
   → Notification → "₹500 sent"
   → Audit → store transaction
   → Fraud → detect suspicious transfer

