5️⃣ Failure Scenarios in Banking Systems

Banking systems must guarantee:

❌ No money loss

❌ No double debit

❌ No partial transfer

❌ No silent failure

So we design for failures first.

Common Real-World Failure Cases
1. Crash After Debit (Most Dangerous)
Debit Account A → SUCCESS
System crashes before Credit → FAILED


Result → Money lost 💥

Solution

Saga Compensation → Refund debit

Transaction status tracking

Retry credit safely

2. Duplicate Transfer (User / Network Retry)
Same transfer executed twice


Result → Double debit 💥

Solution

Idempotency key (transactionId)

Unique DB constraint

Ignore duplicates

3. Service Crash Mid-Transaction
Transfer started → service restarted

Solution

DB Transaction (@Transactional)

Status: PENDING → SUCCESS / FAILED

Recovery job for stuck transactions

4. Event Published Twice (Kafka Redelivery)

Kafka guarantees At-Least-Once → duplicates possible.

Solution

Idempotent consumers

Check transactionId before processing

5. Network Timeout After Success

Client thinks transfer failed → retries → duplicate.

Solution

Idempotency

Return same response for same txnId

6. DB Deadlock / Lock Timeout

Two transfers update same account simultaneously.

Solution

Retry with backoff

Optimistic / Pessimistic locking (Day 9)

Retry Strategy (Banking Standard)

Not all failures are permanent.

Retry for:

Network error

Temporary DB issue

Kafka publish failure

Service timeout

Don’t Retry for:

Insufficient balance

Invalid account

Validation error

Retry with Backoff Example
Try 1 → fail
Wait 1 sec
Try 2 → fail
Wait 2 sec
Try 3 → success


Avoids system overload.

Compensation (Undo) — Saga Concept

If one step fails → undo previous step.

Transfer Example
Step 1: Debit A → SUCCESS
Step 2: Credit B → FAILED

Compensation:
Refund A → SUCCESS


System returns to consistent state.

Transaction Status Tracking (Very Important)
PENDING → SUCCESS → FAILED → REVERSED


Used for:

Recovery

Audit

Retry

Monitoring

